# JavaScript Async Programming Notes (Callbacks → Promises → Async/Await)

---

# 1. Asynchronous JavaScript

JavaScript is **single-threaded**.

When an asynchronous operation starts (network request, timer, file, etc.), JavaScript **does not wait**.

Instead:

- Browser/Node starts the operation.
- JavaScript continues executing other code.
- When the operation finishes, its continuation is scheduled.

Nothing blocks.

---

# 2. Callback

A callback is simply:

> A function passed into another function to be executed later.

Example:

```js
loadScript("script.js", () => {
    console.log("Loaded");
});
```

The callback runs **after** the asynchronous work finishes.

---

# 3. Callback Hell

Nested callbacks create unreadable code.

```js
loadScript("1.js", () => {
    loadScript("2.js", () => {
        loadScript("3.js", () => {
            ...
        });
    });
});
```

Problems

- Deep nesting
- Hard error handling
- Difficult maintenance
- Impossible to scale

Also called:

- Callback Hell
- Pyramid of Doom

---

# 4. Promise

Promise is **NOT the asynchronous task.**

Promise is an object that represents the future result of an asynchronous task.

Think:

```

Async Task <----> Promise <----> Consumer

```

The Promise connects producer and consumer.

---

# Promise States

Initially

```
pending
```

After success

```
fulfilled
```

After failure

```
rejected
```

Once settled:

- State never changes again.
- Extra resolve/reject calls are ignored.

---

# Promise Constructor

```js
const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {

});
```

The executor runs **immediately**.

Not later.

Immediately.

---

# resolve vs reject

Success

```js
resolve(value)
```

Failure

```js
reject(error)
```

Convention:

Always reject with Error objects.

```js
reject(new Error("Something failed"))
```

---

# Promise Consumption

## then()

```js
promise.then(successHandler)
```

or

```js
promise.then(successHandler, errorHandler)
```

---

## catch()

Equivalent to

```js
promise.then(null, errorHandler)
```

Just cleaner.

---

## finally()

Runs regardless of success or failure.

Perfect for:

- cleanup
- hiding loading indicators
- closing connections

Important:

finally()

- receives no arguments
- doesn't modify the result
- passes the value/error through

---

# Promise Chaining

Every `.then()` returns **a brand new Promise.**

```
P1
 |
then
 |
P2
 |
then
 |
P3
```

This is NOT multiple handlers on the same promise.

Each `.then()` creates another Promise.

---

## Multiple .then()

Different.

```js
promise.then(...)
promise.then(...)
promise.then(...)
```

All handlers subscribe to the SAME Promise.

No chaining.

```
        Promise

      /   |   \

 then then then
```

---

Interview Trap

People confuse

```js
.then().then()
```

with

```js
.then()
.then()
.then()
```

Those are completely different.

---

# Error Propagation

Errors automatically travel down the chain.

```
Promise

↓

then

↓

then

↓

catch
```

Any error jumps directly to the nearest catch.

---

# Invisible try...catch

Promise executors automatically have

```
try {

}
catch {

}
```

around them.

Meaning:

```js
throw new Error()
```

is equivalent to

```js
reject(error)
```

Also true inside .then handlers.

---

# Rethrowing

Inside catch:

Handled?

Continue normally.

```js
catch(err){

}
```

Can't handle?

```js
throw err;
```

The next catch receives it.

Exactly like normal try...catch.

---

# Promise APIs

---

## Promise.all()

Wait for ALL.

Returns

```
[value1,value2,value3]
```

Fails immediately if one fails.

Use when every result matters.

---

## Promise.allSettled()

Never fails.

Returns status of every promise.

```
fulfilled

rejected
```

Useful for dashboards, batch operations.

---

## Promise.race()

Returns the FIRST settled promise.

Success OR failure.

---

## Promise.any()

Returns first SUCCESS.

Ignores failures.

Fails only if every promise rejects.

---

# Promisification

Definition:

Convert a callback-based function into a Promise-based function.

Old API

```js
loadScript(src, callback)
```

New API

```js
loadScriptPromise(src)
```

Important idea

We DO NOT rewrite the original function.

Instead we wrap it.

```
Old Callback API

↓

Wrapper

↓

Promise API
```

The wrapper is simply a translator.

```
callback(err,result)

↓

reject(err)

↓

resolve(result)
```

---

Why not

```js
loadScript(src, resolve)
```

Because callback signature is

```js
callback(err,result)
```

while resolve expects

```js
resolve(value)
```

Different signatures.

The wrapper translates between them.

---

Promisify only works correctly if callback executes ONCE.

Promise can settle only once.

---

# Microtask Queue

Most important rule

Promise handlers NEVER execute immediately.

Never.

Even

```js
Promise.resolve(...)
```

still queues its handler.

Example

```js
console.log("A");

Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log("B"));

console.log("C");
```

Output

```
A
C
B
```

Reason

```
Call Stack

↓

Microtask Queue
```

Execution order

1. Finish current stack.
2. Empty microtask queue.

---

Rule to Memorize

JavaScript NEVER interrupts the current Call Stack.

Only when Call Stack becomes empty

↓

Microtasks execute.

---

FIFO

Microtasks execute

First In

↓

First Out

---

# Async / Await

Async/await is syntax sugar over Promises.

It adds NO new asynchronous capability.

Everything still uses Promises underneath.

---

# async

```js
async function f(){

}
```

Always returns a Promise.

Even

```js
return 5;
```

becomes

```js
Promise.resolve(5)
```

---

Equivalent

```js
async function f(){

return 5;

}
```

≈

```js
function f(){

return Promise.resolve(5);

}
```

---

# await

```js
const value = await promise;
```

Pauses ONLY the async function.

Not JavaScript.

Huge difference.

---

Mental Model

```
await

↓

Pause async function

↓

Return control to JavaScript

↓

Promise settles

↓

Resume from exactly here
```

---

Interview Trap

await DOES NOT block JavaScript.

While awaiting

- clicks work
- animations work
- rendering works
- timers continue
- network continues

Only the async function pauses.

---

Example

```js
async function test(){

await Promise.resolve();

console.log("A");

}

test();

console.log("B");
```

Output

```
B
A
```

---

Multiple awaits

Every await creates another continuation.

```js
await ...

↓

resume

↓

await ...

↓

resume
```

Each continuation is another microtask.

---

Error Handling

Use

```js
try{

}
catch{

}
```

instead of

```js
.then().catch()
```

Equivalent behavior.

Rejected Promise

↓

await throws

↓

try...catch catches.

---

Without try...catch

The async function itself becomes a rejected Promise.

```js
f().catch(...)
```

---

# Promise.all with await

Excellent pattern

```js
const [a,b,c] = await Promise.all([
    fetchA(),
    fetchB(),
    fetchC()
]);
```

Runs concurrently.

Not sequentially.

Huge performance improvement.

---

# Common Interview Questions

Q:
Does async make code synchronous?

Answer:
No.

It only makes asynchronous code LOOK synchronous.

---

Q:
Does await block JavaScript?

Answer:
No.

Only pauses the current async function.

---

Q:
Does async create threads?

Answer:
No.

JavaScript remains single-threaded.

---

Q:
Does await skip the Microtask Queue?

Answer:
No.

Continuation always enters the Microtask Queue.

---

Q:
Difference between

```js
.then().then()
```

and

```js
.then()
.then()
.then()
```

First:

Promise chain.

Second:

Multiple subscribers.

---

Q:
Promise vs Async/Await

Async/Await is just cleaner syntax.

Everything still uses Promises.

---

# Senior Mental Model

Think in this order:

```
Call Stack

↓

Browser APIs

↓

Microtask Queue (Promises / await)

↓

Macrotask Queue (Timers, Events...)
```

If this model is clear,

Promises, async/await, Event Loop and browser behavior become much easier to reason about.
